abstract: AN ELOPEMENT.--A young couple, says the Cincinnati Gazette, anxious to assume the responsibilities of conjugal life, left Cleveland on Friday evening, and arrived at Columbus on Saturday morning, where they spent the day. On Sunday morning, they took the morning train for Cincinnati, destined for Aberdeen, the Gretna Green of the State. In the meantime, the papas of both the lovers discovering their absence, had set out in pursuit of the runaways.

abstract: FIRE.--On Thursday night, about 12 o'clock, a fire occurred in a carpenters' shop situated in a vacant lot off Hudson-avenue, near Plymouth-street. The building and contents, consisting of carpenters' tools, were entirely destroyed. Total loss estimates at $400. The building was owned by Dr. FREDERICK MORRIS, and was occupied by a Mr. HENNESSEY. It was supposed to be the work of an incendiary.

abstract: LECTURE VII.--SLAVERY OF ROMANISM. The Tabernacle was agan crowded last evening, on the occasion of Father GAVAZZI'S Seventh Lecture. abstract: NAVAL.--The U. S. Frigate Columbia, Commander PENDERGRAST, bearing the broad pennant of Commodore JOHN THOMAS NEWTON, arrived at this port on Sunday last, twenty-nine days from Norfolk. She came through the Mona passage and along the South side of the Island of St. Domingo. She pursued this safest course, we presume, in consequence of being short-handed, as seafarers observe,-officers, seamen and mariners, numbering in all about three hundred men.

abstract: INCENDIARY FIRE.--THREE BUILDINGS DESTROYED.-Last night. about 12 o'clock, a fire broke out in a three story frame building in the rear of Little-street, opposite Plymouth. The fire spread from this to the one adjoining, fronting on the street; both of these, together with one other, next building on little-street, were nearly destroyed before the flames could be checked.

abstract: MURDER OF A WIFE.--At Fall River, yesterday morning, as we learn from Kinsley's Express, an Irishwoman named NELLY MURPHY, was found dead in bed with her feet firmly tied. From the appearances about the mouth it is supposed that she was murdered by pouring oil of Vitriol down her throat. There were four or five children in the room at the time.

abstract: RAILROAD CASUALTIES.--On Tuesday last, as the Express, going east, on the Erie Railroad, approached Port Jcrvis, the engine struck a rock and was dashed to pieces. The engineer and fireman were almost instantly killed, but the passengers escaped unhurt. The stone which caused this accident had but just fallen on the track--a watchman having passed over the spot eight minutes pre. viously, when all was clear.

abstract: A FRENCH CASSIUS.--A singular sort of fantasy has been lately exhibited by a young Frenchman named BELLEMAR, a native of Rouen. abstract: The State of Delaware is just now in a ferment. abstract: The French are proverbially a tasteful people. They have a fashion of devising ways and means, where a prosaic, matter-of-fact Yankee, or a phlegmatic Dutchman and a Yorkshireman would never dream of anything brilliant. In the application of harsh materials to elegant purposes, they particularly excel.

abstract: From the Washington Union of yesterday. The vague reports which have been lately received from New-Mexico have caused much hasty and improper comment in some quarters. In hot haste to espouse the cause of Mexico, a large portion of the Whig press has already denounced Governor LANE's action as unauthorized annexation, while some have gone so far as to stigmatise it as a violent and piratical spoliation of the territory of a neighboring nation.

abstract: Halifax papers of the 25th inst. are received.
